observations.recommendation:
We recommended the Municipal Mayor to enjoin coordination among the department heads concerned to comply with the requirements of COA Circular No. 2015-008, specifically to require the:
Municipal Engineer to:
Provide the Municipal Accountant and the Property Custodian with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for every road project, as well as the report on the repair/ maintenance of each local road network; and
Reconcile with the Municipal Accounting Office the reports on the Local Road Network.
Property Custodian/ Inventory Committee to:
Conduct an inventory of the local roads under the Municipality’s jurisdiction with the assistance of the Municipal Engineering Office; and to prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network (RPCLRN);
Maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map; and
Maintain a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components and reconcile the same with the records of the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer;
Municipal Accountant to:
Provide the required information in the LRNLC for each Local Road Components with complete description;
Reconcile the LRNLC with the Local Road Inventory and Road Map of the Supply Office and Report on Local Road Network of the Municipal Engineering Office;
Provide the correct depreciation for each road component and make the necessary adjustment to correct the understatement of Accumulated Depreciation recognized for the Road Network account; and
Ensure complete disclosure of the total Road Network System in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Treasurer to:
Issue written notices to payees at least one month before their checks become stale;
Upon presentation of stale checks by the payees, physically cancel and replace them in accordance with Section 59(3) of MNGAS for LGUs;
Reconcile the cashbook balances for Cash in Bank-LCCA accounts with the corresponding ledger balances; and
Prepare cashbooks for Cash in Bank-LCCA accounts for Salintubig, PhilHealth Professional Fee, General Fund-Regular Savings Account (SA) with DBP Account No. 0760-03417-530, General Fund-Regular SA with DBP Account No. 5-13747-760-7, and DBP SA Account No. 0941-0030-10.
We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Cancel all stale checks, revert the amounts to the Cash in Bank account, and record the corresponding Accounts Payable as prescribed in Section 61 of MNGAS for LGUs;
Record Savings Account No. 0941-0030-10 in the books, with a balance of P274,441.65; and
Reconcile ledger balances for Cash in Bank-LCCA accounts with the cashbook balances maintained by the Municipal Treasurer.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
reconcile on a monthly basis, the recorded deductions from payroll with the GSIS Billing Statements and the actual amount remitted to avoid discrepancies;
Maintain a monitoring report detailing the ending balance of the Due to GSIS, indicating the names of employees and their respective balance statuses to facilitate reconciliation;
Identify the employees composing the beginning balance of P80,703.17;
Reconcile and verify the Ending Balance of Prior Years balance amounting to P24,259.67 if it pertains to the unremitted CY 2024 GSIS shown in Annex G; and
Discontinue transferring unremitted GSIS contributions to other accounts solely to clear the “Due to GSIS” account.
We recommended that the Human Resource and Management Office reconcile their records with the GSIS and communicate immediately to the said agency any necessary change in the employees’ employment status to update the records of the GSIS.
We recommend that the Agency Authorized Officers (AAOs) and Electronic Remittance File (ERF) Handlers to reconcile monthly balances and promptly act on any discrepancies.

We recommended to the management to do the following:
Submit immediately to the audit team the following identified relevant supporting documents, in order to substantiate the disbursements made:
Revised POW for the project: Rehabilitation of Multi-purpose Hall at Villa Mangga, Kalingking, supported with valid justification and variation order for the revision made, if warranted;
Daily Time Records (DTRs) of hired laborers;
Appointment orders duly acknowledged by hired laborers;
Certificates of Inspection/Completion, especially those projects with 100% completion duly inspected/signed by the Project Monitoring Committee (PMC);
Certification from the Municipal Accountant that the total labor paid is not more than what was allotted in the POW;
Statements of Work Accomplished (SWA);
Pictures before, during and after the project implementation; if impossible to fully comply all the required pictures, in lieu thereof is a picture upon 100% completion duly conformed by the Punong Barangay where the project is located;
For that specific payroll which was not signed by one recipient, a certification from him certifying that the same was duly received and stating the amount, purpose and period of claim.
Valid justification and separate POW for those additional labor payments made for already finished projects.
Instruct the MAccO to draw a journal entry voucher derecognizing those capitalized expenses for road maintenance. Henceforth, the same transactions should be treated as an outright expense under repairs and maintenance. Further, instruct the MBO to properly account regular road maintenance as MOOE rather than as capital outlay.
Direct the MEO that if a project is already finished and there are unused funds, any new work or improvements (applicable to the same project) not in the original POW must have a separate POW outlining the new scope of work.

We recommended to the management to:
Submit immediately the relevant lacking documents on foreign travel expenses incurred to facilitate our further audit action. Secure documents from LMP-Bukidnon Chapter regarding the breakdown of paid registration fees to accurately account the same, including the pertinent documents necessary for the proper liquidation thereof. Non-submission by management may warrant issuance of audit suspension or disallowance, as the case may be;
Stop the practice of drawing check in favor to the league/association rather than to the concerned personnel to establish accountability over such disbursed amount to be treated as cash advance, subject to proper documentation and liquidation;
Ensure that expenses related to foreign travel be recorded to Travelling Expenses – Foreign account; and,
Strictly observe prudence and judiciousness in the utilization of public funds.

We recommended to the management to immediately submit to the audit team the following relevant documents to facilitate further audit action:
Contract of Service between LGU and the TUPAD workers;
Contract of Service between DOLE Regional Office and the TUPAD workers;
TUPAD Work Program;
Notice to Proceed for the Implementation of the TUPAD Program; and
Sangguniang Bayan Resolution authorizing the LCE to enter into MOA with DOLE.
For future similar payments, the PESO Manager and the Municipal Accountant to ensure that complete documentary requirements are attached to each disbursement voucher/payroll so as not to warrant the audit team’s issuance of audit disallowance or suspension.

We recommended to the management to perform the following: 

a. Hasten the creation of an Appraisal and Disposal Committee who will be responsible for the inspection, appraisal and disposal of those identified unserviceable heavy equipment and other motor vehicles owned by the LGU-Malitbog, strictly adhering with the disposal procedures of the above-mentioned applicable rules and regulations;

b. Submit immediately to the audit team for auditorial review the complete documentary requirements prior review and inspection by the COA Regional Office No. 10’s Regional Technical Audit Group (RTAG); 

c. Resort to proper disposition thru public auction or to other mode of disposal, if deemed appropriate, subject to applicable rules and regulations; and,

d. Treat any proceeds from sale of unserviceable properties as a general income under the General Fund subject for supplemental appropriation to finance priority programs and projects of the municipality.

We recommended to the management to do the following:

Stop the improper practice of granting cash advances without an approved fidelity bond. Instead, designate a duly bonded special disbursing officer/s assigned for specific purpose;

Stop the practice of granting cash advances for travelling expenses in favor to various municipal officials and employees which are improperly cash advanced by one accountable officer, especially to those elective officials. This type of cash advance should be a personal accountability of each personnel;

Ensure that the DV of cash advance is supported with authority to cash advance issued by the LCE and a certification from the Municipal Accountant that the employee has no pending unliquidated cash advances;

Require the Municipal Accountant to record in the books of accounts the said cash advances per concerned employee for proper monitoring and to avoid the granting of additional cash advances to those employees with unliquidated cash advances; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to continue the tracing and reconciliation of general ledgers and subsidiary ledgers of the account “Advances to Officers and Employees” particularly those with unreconciled, negative and unidentified balances.

